515
00:29:21.776 --> 00:29:25.036
They fail just about every therapy, and they are on a deathbed.

516
00:29:25.576 --> 00:29:28.576
So this is dramatic.

517
00:29:29.956 --> 00:29:32.696
Yes. No, I think I agree with you that the

518
00:29:32.876 --> 00:29:34.296
responses

519
00:29:35.836 --> 00:29:39.016
to CAR T-cells in autoimmune disease are dramatic and very exciting.

520
00:29:39.256 --> 00:29:41.716
Yeah. They're not studying routine lupus patients.

521
00:29:41.756 --> 00:29:44.576
These are patients that have basically failed every therapy.

522
00:29:44.676 --> 00:29:45.126
Sure. No.

523
00:29:45.176 --> 00:29:47.076
Every immunosuppressant you want to put on them.

524
00:29:47.516 --> 00:29:48.816
Yeah. Totally agree.

525
00:29:50.696 --> 00:29:52.776
A quick one. I really

526
00:29:53.936 --> 00:29:57.296
like your comment about the fact that we will be able to gain access to T-cell

527
00:29:57.306 --> 00:29:59.656
populations we do not have with ex vivo CAR.

528
00:29:59.796 --> 00:30:03.656
So I'm looking for your perspective on whether we can break that

529
00:30:03.696 --> 00:30:07.536
glass ceiling with solid tumor indications now that we will be able to reach

530
00:30:07.576 --> 00:30:11.216
TLs and TRMs and a bunch of other T-cells that work well or

531
00:30:11.296 --> 00:30:12.976
better in solid tumor indications.

532
00:30:13.176 --> 00:30:15.948
I think it's entirely possible, and I think that's a really-...

533
00:30:15.968 --> 00:30:16.788
exciting

534
00:30:17.708 --> 00:30:21.568
prospect of the near future is now that we know this works in a small

535
00:30:21.588 --> 00:30:25.468
number of patients, but in contexts where ex vivo CAR T cells

536
00:30:25.508 --> 00:30:27.948
do work, of course, that's where you're going to start.

537
00:30:27.968 --> 00:30:31.927
But I think now everyone should start

538
00:30:31.948 --> 00:30:33.268
working on this in solid tumors. Yeah.

539
00:30:33.968 --> 00:30:34.268
Thank you.

540
00:30:35.348 --> 00:30:36.548
One last quick question.

541
00:30:38.908 --> 00:30:42.128
Thank you very much, Dr. Gale. It's really great to see you here again.

542
00:30:42.648 --> 00:30:46.208
You mentioned before in the Tandem conference about your HSC-derived cell

543
00:30:46.268 --> 00:30:50.098
therapies for ex vivo, and this time you mentioned about your in vivo CAR T cell

544
00:30:50.148 --> 00:30:50.698
therapies.

545
00:30:51.548 --> 00:30:54.488
From your vision, what are the differences and what are the modalities that can be

546
00:30:54.548 --> 00:30:56.768
really treated for different disease areas in the future?

547
00:30:56.798 --> 00:30:59.848
And would you see those growing in parallel or one replacing the other?

548
00:30:59.968 --> 00:31:01.708
I would love to answer that, but that's not a quick

549
00:31:02.728 --> 00:31:04.278
one, so maybe we can chat afterwards.

550
00:31:04.408 --> 00:31:04.948
Okay. Thank you.

551
00:31:05.128 --> 00:31:05.608
Yeah.

552
00:31:05.688 --> 00:31:07.768
Okay, great. That may be a good panel question.

553
00:31:08.608 --> 00:31:12.188
Our next speaker is Dr. Crystal Mackall from Stanford

554
00:31:12.268 --> 00:31:16.178
University, and Crystal is going to talk to us about CAR T cells

555
00:31:16.588 --> 00:31:18.368
for pediatric brain tumors.

556
00:31:21.387 --> 00:31:24.128
Good afternoon, everyone, and thank you, Drs.

557
00:31:24.168 --> 00:31:24.948
Lu and Small,

558
00:31:26.828 --> 00:31:30.108
for the invitation. Pleasure to be here.

559
00:31:30.508 --> 00:31:34.358
Here are my disclosures. So I'm going to talk to you today about the efforts

560
00:31:34.388 --> 00:31:37.928
that we have underway to develop CAR T cells for a lethal

561
00:31:37.968 --> 00:31:39.308
pediatric brain tumor.

562
00:31:40.368 --> 00:31:43.968
It also actually occurs in adults, but it's well-known for

563
00:31:43.988 --> 00:31:45.368
afflicting school-aged children.

564
00:31:45.398 --> 00:31:49.168
And you can see there that the median overall survival is dismal.

565
00:31:49.228 --> 00:31:52.488
Essentially, no patients survive this tumor.

566
00:31:52.548 --> 00:31:54.728
And we know a lot about its biology.

567
00:31:54.758 --> 00:31:57.848
It's driven by a mutation in the H3 histone

568
00:31:58.708 --> 00:32:01.868
that leads to widespread transcriptional

569
00:32:01.948 --> 00:32:05.208
dysregulation. And it turns out that this

570
00:32:05.768 --> 00:32:09.028
H3 histone axis is the axis that controls

571
00:32:09.788 --> 00:32:13.388
production of gangliosides. And as a

572
00:32:13.448 --> 00:32:16.988
result, these tumors massively overexpress

573
00:32:17.928 --> 00:32:21.268
the fatty sugar GD2, the so-called disialo

574
00:32:21.288 --> 00:32:24.388
ganglioside, really at levels in the

575
00:32:24.448 --> 00:32:27.857
millions of molecules per cell.

576
00:32:28.328 --> 00:32:31.988
And just for context, CD19 is

577
00:32:32.028 --> 00:32:35.748
expressed at about 50,000 molecules per cell on B cells.

578
00:32:35.828 --> 00:32:37.728
So it's really massively overexpressed.

579
00:32:38.548 --> 00:32:42.468
Michel Mange's lab made this discovery back in 2017,

580
00:32:43.448 --> 00:32:47.308
and we began collaborating because we had been working on developing a CAR T cell

581
00:32:47.768 --> 00:32:49.178
targeting GD2. And

582
00:32:50.048 --> 00:32:54.008
try as we might to develop new binders to this fatty sugar,

583
00:32:54.128 --> 00:32:57.428
we haven't been able to. And so we've been stuck with this

584
00:32:57.548 --> 00:33:01.158
mouse-derived anti-GD2 single-chain Fv that was

585
00:33:01.168 --> 00:33:04.738
developed in the 1980s. Nonetheless, this

586
00:33:04.768 --> 00:33:08.348
GD2 CAR, after intravenous infusion in neonatal

587
00:33:08.388 --> 00:33:12.128
mice that are implanted with these tumors in their midbrain,

588
00:33:12.848 --> 00:33:15.548
cured these mice with one intravenous infusion.

589
00:33:16.098 --> 00:33:18.448
And we also studied the efficacy of

590
00:33:18.588 --> 00:33:22.388
intracerebroventricular CAR T cells in the setting

591
00:33:22.508 --> 00:33:26.137
of this and other brain tumors. And what we learned is that both worked,

592
00:33:26.628 --> 00:33:29.508
but intracerebroventricular delivery was more potent.

593
00:33:29.548 --> 00:33:33.268
And in fact, we needed about tenfold less T cells if we were

594
00:33:33.288 --> 00:33:35.128
delivering them directly into the brain.

595
00:33:35.188 --> 00:33:39.128
And even when we directly infused them into the brain, they

596
00:33:39.188 --> 00:33:42.188
did traffic to the periphery and often were sustained.

597
00:33:42.228 --> 00:33:46.168
And this is a teaser for what I'm going to talk about today, but you can see

598
00:33:46.268 --> 00:33:49.848
several months out in these mice, you still find these T cells

599
00:33:49.888 --> 00:33:53.608
circulating. So we had the opportunity now to translate this by

600
00:33:53.668 --> 00:33:57.477
either administering CAR T cells intravenously into these

601
00:33:57.508 --> 00:34:00.548
children or intracerebroventricularly or

602
00:34:00.608 --> 00:34:04.548
intracranially. And so we decided to hedge our bets on the

603
00:34:04.588 --> 00:34:07.828
first rollout of this trial, so-called Arm A.

604
00:34:08.268 --> 00:34:11.308
And basically, patients were required to have the mutation.

605
00:34:11.688 --> 00:34:15.669
They had an Ommaya reservoir placed, which is the catheter that allows

606
00:34:15.708 --> 00:34:18.308
us to administer these cells into the brain.

607
00:34:18.348 --> 00:34:22.028
And the first infusion was intravenous after standard lymphodepletion.

608
00:34:22.569 --> 00:34:26.538
If the patient did well and showed some evidence of benefit, they could

609
00:34:26.548 --> 00:34:30.528
receive sequential intracerebroventricular infusions, and we

610
00:34:30.569 --> 00:34:33.288
didn't give additional lymphodepletion before those.

611
00:34:33.328 --> 00:34:37.008
And you can see the team that worked together to get this trial launched.

612
00:34:37.109 --> 00:34:40.848
Now, the results from Arm A were published a few years ago,

613
00:34:41.368 --> 00:34:45.169
and overall, there was clear evidence for clinical activity.

614
00:34:45.589 --> 00:34:48.448
Thirteen patients were enrolled, and 11 were treated.

615
00:34:49.288 --> 00:34:52.808
And we saw significant numbers of patients with major tumor shrinkage.

616
00:34:53.308 --> 00:34:56.468
Now, for this disease, where there is no standard upfront therapy

617
00:34:56.478 --> 00:35:00.308
besides palliative radiotherapy, to see this type of

618
00:35:00.348 --> 00:35:03.068
regressions was really quite notable.

619
00:35:03.528 --> 00:35:07.268
The median overall survival typically for this disease is nine to 11

620
00:35:07.328 --> 00:35:11.188
months, and we saw a very favorable median overall survival

621
00:35:11.208 --> 00:35:13.948
despite the caveats of a single-arm trial.

622
00:35:13.958 --> 00:35:17.178
And perhaps most gratifying, we saw substantial clinical

623
00:35:17.288 --> 00:35:21.088
benefit in many patients. And in particular, this was the

624
00:35:21.148 --> 00:35:24.488
patient number 10. He was 17 when he was enrolled, and he's

625
00:35:24.548 --> 00:35:28.308
achieved a complete response that's been ongoing for over

626
00:35:28.388 --> 00:35:32.268
four years from enrollment. And when he came to us, he

627
00:35:32.328 --> 00:35:35.948
was able to walk, but really not very far, and used a

628
00:35:36.008 --> 00:35:39.928
wheelchair for any distance and had stopped going to high school because

629
00:35:39.948 --> 00:35:43.588
he was homebound. And so here he is one month after his first

630
00:35:43.648 --> 00:35:46.768
infusion. You can see his father has to help him walk

631
00:35:47.568 --> 00:35:51.238
because he's had so much neurologic compromise.

632
00:35:51.808 --> 00:35:55.648
Eight months after the first infusion, he's obviously walking on his own,

633
00:35:55.708 --> 00:35:59.348
and he subsequently went on to go away to college and complete his

634
00:35:59.368 --> 00:36:02.848
degree and travel Europe and do all the normal things.

635
00:36:02.928 --> 00:36:05.408
So the good news is we did have clinical activity.

636
00:36:05.898 --> 00:36:09.528
The bad news is, as it's often in cancer medicine, we saw some

637
00:36:09.588 --> 00:36:12.848
significant toxicity. One of the major

638
00:36:12.888 --> 00:36:16.668
toxicities was high-grade cytokine release syndrome

639
00:36:16.678 --> 00:36:20.228
after the intravenous infusion. You can see there.

640
00:36:20.268 --> 00:36:23.808
We did not see cytokine release syndrome after the subsequent

641
00:36:23.848 --> 00:36:27.636
intracerebroventricular infusion.We did

642
00:36:27.676 --> 00:36:30.436
define a new toxicity, so-called tumor

643
00:36:31.136 --> 00:36:35.096
inflammation-associated neurotoxicity, and this is related to swelling of

644
00:36:35.136 --> 00:36:38.456
the tumor that leads to neurologic compromise or increased intracranial

645
00:36:38.476 --> 00:36:42.416
pressure. This was not dose-limiting and could be managed with careful

646
00:36:42.515 --> 00:36:45.076
monitoring and treatment algorithms.

647
00:36:46.516 --> 00:36:50.476
Now, one of the clues that we uncovered as we looked at the correlative

648
00:36:50.516 --> 00:36:54.436
results in the patients treated on arm A, were that the patients who tended to

649
00:36:54.476 --> 00:36:58.386
do better tended to have more prolonged persistence of the GD2 CAR in their

650
00:36:58.456 --> 00:37:02.026
bloodstream. This is patient 10, our durable responder,

651
00:37:02.416 --> 00:37:05.555
and his CAR T cells were circulating for over a year.

652
00:37:05.596 --> 00:37:09.496
Here's patient number six, who had good levels in her bloodstream for the first

653
00:37:09.506 --> 00:37:13.276
three months, but then subsequently relapsed, and you can see her cell-free

654
00:37:13.356 --> 00:37:16.816
DNA recurring about the time her CAR Ts disappear.

655
00:37:16.936 --> 00:37:20.036
So this gave us a hint that persistence mattered.

656
00:37:20.776 --> 00:37:24.545
All right. So at this point, we had favorable survival, but this

657
00:37:24.556 --> 00:37:26.446
dose-limiting cytokine release syndrome.

658
00:37:26.936 --> 00:37:30.536
So we modified the trial, and we said, "Let's get rid of the intravenous

659
00:37:30.656 --> 00:37:33.956
infusion, and let's put the cells where the tumor

660
00:37:34.036 --> 00:37:37.956
is." And so we gave them intracerebroventricularly,

661
00:37:38.176 --> 00:37:41.916
without any previous lymphodepletion and without any

662
00:37:41.976 --> 00:37:45.816
intravenous infusion. And unfortunately, the results

663
00:37:45.856 --> 00:37:49.756
were not as good. Patients had transient responses, but they would

664
00:37:49.836 --> 00:37:52.036
rarely last longer than two to three months.

665
00:37:52.676 --> 00:37:56.656
And while the cytokine release syndrome was gone, we really felt

666
00:37:56.666 --> 00:38:00.516
we had lost our efficacy. And when you look at the persistence of

667
00:38:00.556 --> 00:38:04.476
patients in the bloodstream, all of the patients enrolled on arm A, you see

668
00:38:04.516 --> 00:38:08.316
we had this very nice persistence of the GD2 CAR T cells, but

669
00:38:08.376 --> 00:38:11.676
very poor persistence, really, in the bloodstream or even in the

670
00:38:11.716 --> 00:38:15.516
CNS of patients enrolled on arm B, where we took the

671
00:38:15.536 --> 00:38:19.146
lymphodepletion away. And so this led us to think that

672
00:38:19.176 --> 00:38:23.066
perhaps immune responses to the CAR T cells were limiting

673
00:38:23.096 --> 00:38:26.996
CAR T cell persistence in arm B and preventing

674
00:38:27.036 --> 00:38:30.836
disease control. And maybe the lymphodepletion we gave on arm

675
00:38:30.956 --> 00:38:31.496
A

676
00:38:32.336 --> 00:38:35.495
prevented these immune rejection.

677
00:38:35.576 --> 00:38:38.766
So we went looking for these immune responses, and the first thing we did was a

678
00:38:38.896 --> 00:38:42.296
cell-based assay looking for circulating

679
00:38:42.376 --> 00:38:45.106
anti-CAR antibodies, an old-fashioned assay.

680
00:38:45.556 --> 00:38:48.716
We expressed GD2 CAR on the surface of a T cell.

681
00:38:48.756 --> 00:38:51.776
We come in with patient serum or a control

682
00:38:51.856 --> 00:38:55.836
anti-idiotype, and then we do a sandwich assay looking for the presence

683
00:38:55.896 --> 00:38:59.596
of cell-bound antibody. And indeed, we found them in

684
00:38:59.656 --> 00:39:03.436
most patients, and the level of these anti-CAR antibodies

685
00:39:03.876 --> 00:39:07.776
in the plasma was inversely related to the persistence of the CAR

686
00:39:07.796 --> 00:39:11.196
T cells, consistent with our hypothesis.

687
00:39:11.256 --> 00:39:14.776
When you take the serum from these patients in the presence of these anti-CAR

688
00:39:14.816 --> 00:39:18.156
antibodies and you incubate it at the time you

689
00:39:18.196 --> 00:39:22.146
inoculate CAR T cells with these tumor cells, you see that

690
00:39:22.176 --> 00:39:24.536
the serum interferes with killing.

691
00:39:24.556 --> 00:39:28.316
Look at the dashed lines compared to the solid lines for each of

692
00:39:28.376 --> 00:39:32.336
the various dilutions. So these antibodies

693
00:39:32.356 --> 00:39:35.676
were directly capable of impeding CAR killing.

694
00:39:35.696 --> 00:39:39.096
And in several cases, we noted that the onset of the

695
00:39:39.176 --> 00:39:43.016
antibodies temporally correlated with loss of

696
00:39:43.056 --> 00:39:46.636
circulating GD2 CAR T cells. Look at patient number six here.

697
00:39:47.056 --> 00:39:49.316
Here are the circulating GD2 CAR T cells.

698
00:39:49.696 --> 00:39:53.536
About the time the human anti-CAR antibodies appear in the serum,

699
00:39:53.936 --> 00:39:57.336
we see the CAR T cells disappear. This is the clinical result.

700
00:39:57.656 --> 00:40:01.356
This patient had a response in green, and then soon after that, had

701
00:40:01.416 --> 00:40:05.106
progression. Here's patient number nine, who had very good

702
00:40:05.196 --> 00:40:08.816
persistence of his CAR T cells until the onset of the anti-CAR

703
00:40:08.896 --> 00:40:12.836
antibodies in the blood, ultimately followed by relapse.

704
00:40:13.496 --> 00:40:16.816
Now, we have an extensive single-cell atlas that's been

705
00:40:16.856 --> 00:40:20.656
interrogated by Yuyun Chen, who's in the audience and will be presenting her poster

706
00:40:21.296 --> 00:40:24.796
tomorrow, number 6463. I encourage folks who are

707
00:40:24.836 --> 00:40:28.336
interested to look at it. But this is providing us with immense

708
00:40:28.496 --> 00:40:31.956
information about the immune responses that are happening in the

709
00:40:32.016 --> 00:40:35.236
CNS of these patients treated with CAR T cells.

710
00:40:35.726 --> 00:40:36.096
So

711
00:40:36.996 --> 00:40:39.916
overall, when you step back and you say, "What is in the

712
00:40:40.436 --> 00:40:44.396
CSF of these patients after each cycle?" And

713
00:40:44.415 --> 00:40:46.156
these are their mean levels.

714
00:40:47.056 --> 00:40:50.596
You can see that the hatched marks here are the CAR T cells.

715
00:40:51.136 --> 00:40:54.966
The orange hatch is CD4 CARs, and the blue hatch are

716
00:40:54.996 --> 00:40:58.556
CD8 CARs. And you see they don't make up much of the cells in the

717
00:40:58.616 --> 00:41:02.016
CSF, and they're really only present in any significant

718
00:41:02.076 --> 00:41:03.936
quantity during the early cycles.

719
00:41:03.956 --> 00:41:07.896
By the time you get to the later cycles, you find almost no CAR T

720
00:41:07.976 --> 00:41:11.916
cells in the CNS, even though we're administering them about once a

721
00:41:11.956 --> 00:41:15.856
month. If you look at non-CAR T cells, those are the blue and the

722
00:41:15.976 --> 00:41:19.676
orange, there are plenty of non-CAR T cells in that CNS.

723
00:41:20.336 --> 00:41:22.956
And if you look at the clonality using single-cell

724
00:41:23.016 --> 00:41:26.796
TCR-seq, you see that the CAR T

725
00:41:26.876 --> 00:41:29.916
cells in the CNS that are present are not clonally

726
00:41:29.956 --> 00:41:33.936
expanded. Whereas the CAR-negative cells, presumably

727
00:41:33.976 --> 00:41:37.716
derived from endogenous T cells, show significant

728
00:41:37.756 --> 00:41:40.536
clonal expansion. Here's another way of looking at this.

729
00:41:41.296 --> 00:41:44.876
The CAR-negative cells here, now we're following the top 20

730
00:41:44.916 --> 00:41:47.316
clonotypes in these CAR-negative T cells.

731
00:41:47.736 --> 00:41:51.496
And you can see that once these clonotypes show up, they

732
00:41:51.556 --> 00:41:55.296
largely persist over time. And sometimes during these late

733
00:41:55.336 --> 00:41:59.296
time points associated with disease progression, they increase, both

734
00:41:59.336 --> 00:42:03.076
in patient six and patient nine. But look at the CAR positive T

735
00:42:03.156 --> 00:42:06.876
cells. They come in, and they disappear, and they are not sustained.

736
00:42:07.456 --> 00:42:10.016
Here's our patient number 10, our complete responder.

737
00:42:10.436 --> 00:42:13.996
He's got an onset of these CAR-negative cells in his

738
00:42:14.056 --> 00:42:15.676
CNS, but they eventually get

739
00:42:16.716 --> 00:42:19.976
diminished. In fact, they did not sustain over time,

740
00:42:20.576 --> 00:42:24.176
really suggesting to us that these CAR-negative T cells that are clonally

741
00:42:24.196 --> 00:42:27.768
expanding in the CNS may bePlaying a

742
00:42:27.848 --> 00:42:30.868
part in the rejection. So Max Koch from the

743
00:42:31.648 --> 00:42:32.948
Heisenator Lab

744
00:42:33.888 --> 00:42:37.838
really went to look for the anti-CAR T cell responses, and

745
00:42:37.838 --> 00:42:41.728
he found them broadly. These are CD4 anti-CAR T

746
00:42:41.788 --> 00:42:44.308
cell responses making IL-2 and interferon gamma.

747
00:42:44.788 --> 00:42:48.768
You can see very clearly these are quite robust, and this is the population as

748
00:42:48.808 --> 00:42:52.608
a whole showing high levels of anti-CAR T cell responses.

749
00:42:52.648 --> 00:42:54.908
Here are the CD8 responses,

750
00:42:55.848 --> 00:42:58.408
degranulating and upregulating 4-1BB.

751
00:42:58.928 --> 00:43:02.338
Again, very high levels of anti-CAR T cell responses.

752
00:43:02.948 --> 00:43:06.608
Using an overlapping peptide library, Max was able to map these

753
00:43:06.648 --> 00:43:10.328
responses. And not surprisingly, they mapped in large

754
00:43:10.388 --> 00:43:14.248
part to the mouse-derived single-chain Fv from the old

755
00:43:14.348 --> 00:43:16.478
antibody from which we made the CAR.

756
00:43:16.508 --> 00:43:20.428
They also mapped to the junctional domains, where you create a

757
00:43:20.468 --> 00:43:24.248
non-native protein where 4-1BB and

758
00:43:24.648 --> 00:43:28.628
zeta, for instance, overlap. But in some cases, they actually overlapped

759
00:43:28.668 --> 00:43:32.088
on fully human components like Icaspase-9.

760
00:43:32.768 --> 00:43:35.888
So these patients are generating robust

761
00:43:35.988 --> 00:43:39.348
CD4, CD8, and anti-CAR antibody

762
00:43:39.388 --> 00:43:43.028
responses in the blood. Now let's go back to the

763
00:43:43.068 --> 00:43:46.918
CSF and look for B cells in the CSF. And indeed, you see them

764
00:43:46.948 --> 00:43:50.408
show up in some patients, usually associated at the time of

765
00:43:50.428 --> 00:43:52.668
progression and increasing with time.

766
00:43:52.688 --> 00:43:56.668
And in general, the more B cells that you found in the CSF, the

767
00:43:56.708 --> 00:44:00.528
worse the patient did on those cycles. It was trended that way.

768
00:44:01.188 --> 00:44:04.988
Now, were the B cells in the CNS actually producing anti-CAR

769
00:44:05.048 --> 00:44:08.108
antibodies? Now again, we take those top 10

770
00:44:08.388 --> 00:44:09.128
clonotypes,

771
00:44:09.988 --> 00:44:13.148
and we now express those genes in

772
00:44:13.988 --> 00:44:17.768
a line that's capable of producing antibodies, and then we check to see, does the

773
00:44:17.828 --> 00:44:20.668
antibody bind the CAR expressing T cells?

774
00:44:21.028 --> 00:44:23.048
And you can see indeed, most of the top

775
00:44:24.008 --> 00:44:27.108
clonotypes found in the CNS actually bind

776
00:44:27.188 --> 00:44:30.998
cell-associated GD2 CAR. Now, for those of us that aren't

777
00:44:31.188 --> 00:44:34.938
CNS immunobiologists, and I don't think very few of us are, it turns

778
00:44:35.068 --> 00:44:38.968
out that most of these were of the IgA isotype.

779
00:44:38.988 --> 00:44:42.368
And this surprised us because generally, we think of early

780
00:44:42.388 --> 00:44:46.228
antibodies in the circulation, et cetera, being IgG, but many of

781
00:44:46.248 --> 00:44:50.108
these were IgA, and it turns out that meningeal lymphatics

782
00:44:50.118 --> 00:44:51.537
are enriched with

783
00:44:51.628 --> 00:44:55.248
IgA-producing B cells, which have

784
00:44:55.308 --> 00:44:57.528
evidently been educated in the gut.

785
00:44:57.548 --> 00:45:01.108
And so we think this provides very strong evidence that

786
00:45:01.488 --> 00:45:04.488
some of these anti-CAR antibody responses are actually being produced

787
00:45:04.608 --> 00:45:07.388
within the CNS, not just in the periphery.

788
00:45:08.008 --> 00:45:10.537
Okay, so here we are. What do we do now?

789
00:45:10.628 --> 00:45:14.588
We realize that we've backed off on the lymphodepletion, and now we've lost our

790
00:45:14.608 --> 00:45:17.738
response. So we added lymphodepletion back.

791
00:45:18.228 --> 00:45:22.097
Now we're administering ICV only and giving lymphodepletion

792
00:45:22.168 --> 00:45:26.108
about every four cycles. And now we start to see very

793
00:45:26.128 --> 00:45:29.808
durable responses, and you can see our current

794
00:45:29.877 --> 00:45:32.408
data from this trial, which is ongoing.

795
00:45:32.948 --> 00:45:36.808
Arm C is the arm where we're giving intracerebroventricular CAR

796
00:45:36.828 --> 00:45:40.668
T cells only with lymphodepletion approximately every four

797
00:45:40.708 --> 00:45:44.188
cycles. We've now added rituximab on another arm,

798
00:45:44.588 --> 00:45:47.127
Arm D, and it's too early to present that data.

799
00:45:47.488 --> 00:45:51.368
But for this disease, for which there really has never been any therapy

800
00:45:51.728 --> 00:45:55.668
that could lead to durable responses, we're quite

801
00:45:55.708 --> 00:45:57.568
excited about these results on Arm C.

802
00:45:58.408 --> 00:46:02.248
So GD2 CAR T cells induce impressive responses associated with

803
00:46:02.288 --> 00:46:04.928
prolonged survival in diffuse midline gliomas.

804
00:46:05.508 --> 00:46:09.488
The resistance that we've found in this setting is associated with anti-CAR

805
00:46:09.528 --> 00:46:12.588
immune responses, both in the CSF and the periphery.

806
00:46:13.168 --> 00:46:17.108
These results align with our emerging understanding of neuroimmunology.

807
00:46:17.468 --> 00:46:21.428
We've talked about the CNS as immune privileged, but in fact, there is

808
00:46:21.448 --> 00:46:25.428
significant crosstalk between the CNS and the peripheral immune system.

809
00:46:25.458 --> 00:46:29.248
And the bias we talked about toward IgA antibodies suggests that

810
00:46:29.268 --> 00:46:33.148
some of this response, at least, is likely initiated in

811
00:46:33.168 --> 00:46:35.788
the CNS or in the peri-CNS tissues.

812
00:46:36.388 --> 00:46:39.928
Now, this means that lymphodepletion, even though we'd like to get rid of it,

813
00:46:40.348 --> 00:46:43.968
it's a critical component of a successful CAR T cell regimen in this

814
00:46:44.048 --> 00:46:47.068
setting, and this may generalize to other brain tumors.

815
00:46:47.787 --> 00:46:50.828
I think we've all heard that causes for

816
00:46:51.388 --> 00:46:55.328
limited CAR T cell responses in solid tumors relate to

817
00:46:55.368 --> 00:46:59.268
problems like T cell exhaustion, suppressive microenvironment, but I

818
00:46:59.288 --> 00:47:02.908
think we need to add immunogenicity to this list.

819
00:47:03.568 --> 00:47:07.528
And we all know that stealth platforms were developed for allogeneic CAR T

820
00:47:07.588 --> 00:47:11.348
cells. These data suggest that perhaps we should be using stealth platforms

821
00:47:11.748 --> 00:47:15.248
in the context of auto-CAR T cells in solid tumors.

822
00:47:15.818 --> 00:47:19.228
And then finally, this is a negative for these patients.

823
00:47:19.688 --> 00:47:23.568
But when you see this consistent breadth and very

824
00:47:23.688 --> 00:47:27.408
strong immune response that's induced by CAR T cells, it

825
00:47:27.448 --> 00:47:30.648
raises the prospect that we could exploit this by

826
00:47:30.708 --> 00:47:34.068
co-delivering CAR T cells with a regimen optimized for

827
00:47:34.108 --> 00:47:36.668
vaccinating against the tumor antigen.

828
00:47:36.688 --> 00:47:38.618
And so I think that's something that should be considered.

829
00:47:39.098 --> 00:47:41.418
So this has taken really a very large team.

830
00:47:41.568 --> 00:47:45.148
I want to highlight the work of Michel Mange, who I've done all of this work very

831
00:47:45.188 --> 00:47:49.168
closely hand in hand with, Kunwei Song, Jasi Amade, other

832
00:47:49.208 --> 00:47:52.988
neuro-oncologists, our pediatric cancer cell therapist, Neha Ramakrishna,

833
00:47:53.348 --> 00:47:57.018
has played a leading role in the correlative science, as well as Bita Sahaf, our

834
00:47:57.088 --> 00:48:01.068
collaborators, Sabine, Zena, Max Koch, Elena,

835
00:48:01.148 --> 00:48:04.928
Yeyun Chen, who led the single-cell RNA-seq, and Kevin Reynolds, who really

836
00:48:04.988 --> 00:48:08.208
led the work on the antibodies. Thank you very much.

837
00:48:09.488 --> 00:48:12.948
Thank you very much, Crystal. We have time for a couple of

838
00:48:13.328 --> 00:48:15.928
quick questions. If there are any, please come up to the

839
00:48:16.308 --> 00:48:17.468
microphone.

840
00:48:18.748 --> 00:48:22.288
I think one over there.

841
00:48:25.668 --> 00:48:26.368
Please go ahead.

842
00:48:26.968 --> 00:48:28.608
Thank you. That was a very interesting talk.

